Wajir governor Mohamed Abdi got some reprieve on Friday after the Supreme Court allowed him to bring in new evidence in support of his case.This means the governor will be in office until his case is determined by the court.The governor’s election was nullified by the High Court and Court of Appeal but he moved to the Supreme Court seeking to overturn the decision.Former Wajir governor Ahmed Abdullahi, who ran on the ODM ticket, challenged Abdi’s victory.The two lower courts sent him home for alleged lack of academic paper. Read: Wajir Governor Abdi appeals High court decision nullifying his winBut on Friday the Supreme Court held that he did not get a fair trial at the lower courts and allowed him to bring evidence to support his claims that he has the right academic papers.The court also allowed the deputy governor to be enjoined in the case. Six judges ruled that the evidence to be submitted will not be prejudicial to the other parties.They said the court’s rules allows them to admit new evidence but the powers should be used sparingly. The judges ruled that they were not convinced that Abdi was given a fair hearing.In his application, Abdi said the judges had attacked his education credentials yet he holds a degree from Kampala University which is accredited by the Commission for Higher Education.Through lawyer Tom Macharia, Abdi said he will show the court how Parliament waived the requirement, from a constitutional perspective.DiscrepanciesThe Court of Appeal upheld a decision by Justice Alfred Mabeya of the High Court that nullified his election on grounds that his academic papers were questionable and so he was ineligible to run for election last year.Judges Phillip Waki, Patrick Kiage and Milton Makhandia ruled that Abdi wasted a chance to tell his side of the story when he failed to respond to the allegation raised against him.Mabeya ruled that Abdi was not validly cleared to run for governor and pointed out discrepancies in Form 37B. “The election was not fair and credible as required by the Electoral Laws Act,” he said, adding voters were assisted in the process, thereby compromising integrity. Mabeya cited irregularities including the opening of some of the ballot boxes that had been sealed. The court also found that some forms had alterations yet there were no counter-signatures as required by the law. Read: Abdi appeal listed urgent by Mwilu Click here for
the latest political news